title: Kentucky falls at Florida, loses top SEC spot

\John Calipari talks UK's loss to Florida Fletcher Page, the CJ
Feb 4, 2017; Gainesville, FL, USA; Kentucky Wildcats head coach John Calipari reacts against the Florida Gators during the first half at Exactech Arena at the Stephen C. O'Connell Center. (Photo: Kim Klement-USA TODAY Sports)
GAINESVILLE, Fla. â€“ Kentucky is no longer atop the Southeastern Conference standings.
The No. 6 Wildcats fell at No. 23 Florida 88-66 Saturday night and were replaced by South Carolina as the top team in the league.
Kentucky (18-5, 8-2) did not play like a team seeking to re-assert dominance and lock down a No. 1 seed in the NCAA tournament in front of a sold-out crowd at O'Connell Center. Florida (18-5, 8-2), instead, emerged as a contender in the league and nationally, behind Kasey Hill's 21 points and a supreme defensive and rebounding performance.
"I told the guys, 'hey, beating Kentucky is great,'" Florida coach Mike White said. "They're one of the best teams in the country, but we are, too."
Devin Robinson had 16 points for the Gators, with Canyon Barry adding 14 and KeVaughn Hill 12. De'Aaron Fox paced Kentucky with 19 points and Malik Monk had 11.
The Wildcats entered with a five-game winning streak against the Gators, but Kentucky's recent string of sub-par play, in two losses to Tennessee and Kansas and an overtime win over Georgia, was exposed and amplified for all to see once again. The game was tied for 28 seconds at the beginning and Florida took and held control the rest of the way.
"We have to go back and get in the groove of how we're playing," Kentucky coach John Calipari said.
Monk, the SEC's leading scorer, missed his first seven shots and didn't score until nearly four minutes into the second half. He finished with the second-lowest total in his career, on 4-of-14 shooting.
Fox did not start due to lingering effects of the flu illness that kept him out of the Georgia game. Still, the freshman point guard logged 25 minutes and sank a career-high 9 of 10 at the free throw line.
"It was kind of difficult, my legs weren't under me, but people play through sickness," Fox said. "I'm back now, so I'm not going to give any excuses."
Fox's trips to the stripe were not nearly enough and there would be no heroics from Monk to save the day like he did against the Bulldogs.
Florida built a 23-point lead in the second half, the largest deficit Kentucky has faced this season and finished off the worst loss for Kentucky since a 19-point drubbing here against the Gators in March of 2014. Florida out-rebounded the Wildcats 52-29 and limited UK, a team constantly looking to push the pace and score quick, to only eight fastbreak points.
The Gamecocks beat Georgia earlier in the day to move to 9-1 in the conference, one game ahead of Kentucky and Florida. The Wildcats beat South Carolina 85-69 last month at Rupp Arena and the two do not meet again in the regular season. Florida still has match-ups with both the Wildcats and the Gamecocks, two meetings that will likely decide the conference champion.
Next up, Kentucky hosts LSU, Florida plays at Georgia and South Carolina hosts Alabama on Tuesday.
